result.execSummary:
Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Reggie L Amborn in court with attorney Mandy Lynn Caffee.  James Jay Rennicke appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Heard along with 16CM99, 16TR280.  Agreement has been reached in all matters, State recites settlement into the court record.  Court instructs on plea questionnaire/waiver of rights.  DE will enter a plea to Ct 1 in 16CT29, all other counts and cases will be DRI.  

16CT29-DE enters a plea of G, court accepts, finds the DE guilty.  Court will accept the recommendations of the parties.  Court will order a fine of $2547.00, 110 days jail w/huber, restitution of $22.90, Revocation of DL for a 30 month, IID for 30 months.  PP of $50.00 per month, commencing the first day of the first full month after release from jail.
